# DIG Browser: dock the DIG Wallet (dig://wallet) and DIG Shields
# (dig://shields) surfaces into Chromium's built-in Side Panel.
#
# PROBLEM this fixes (#114): the wallet + shields toolbar buttons previously
# opened their dig:// surfaces with NavigateParams + WindowOpenDisposition::
# NEW_POPUP -- i.e. as FREE-FLOATING popup OS windows merely *positioned* at the
# edge of the browser window. They never used Chromium's Side Panel, so they did
# not actually dock (they floated, could be dragged off, and didn't reserve
# layout space). The user reported exactly this.
#
# FIX: register dig://wallet and dig://shields as GLOBAL (window-scoped)
# SidePanelEntry objects so they open DOCKED in the real Side Panel from any tab.
# This patch carries the shared side-panel plumbing; the toolbar buttons are
# rewired to drive it in windows-dig-browser-ux.patch (wallet / home_button.cc)
# and windows-dig-shields.patch (DigShieldsButton).
#
# Mechanism (verified against the Chromium 149 Side Panel headers):
#   * Two new SidePanelEntryId values -- kDigWallet, kDigShields -- added to the
#     SIDE_PANEL_ENTRY_IDS macro in side_panel_entry_id.h, each with a
#     std::nullopt action id, mirroring the existing kWebView / kSidePanelDev
#     generic entries. (The registry keys entries by id and rejects duplicates,
#     so each docked surface needs its OWN id; the single kWebView id can host
#     only one entry per registry.) The macro drives the To-String / histogram /
#     action-id switches automatically, so no exhaustive switch breaks.
#   * dig_side_panel.{h,cc}: RegisterDigSidePanelEntries() builds, for each
#     surface, a SidePanelEntry whose CreateContentCallback returns a plain
#     views::WebView (profile-bound) that LoadInitialURL()s the dig:// surface.
#     The dig:// scheme is served in-process by the DIG URLLoaderFactory for
#     navigations + subresources (windows-dig-browser-ux.patch), so the docked
#     WebView renders the SAME page the popup did -- verified + decrypted the
#     same way. The page HTML/JS is UNCHANGED.
#   * The entries are registered HEADER-LESS (set_should_show_header(false)): a
#     std::nullopt-action entry must skip SidePanelHeaderController, whose
#     SidePanelHelper::GetActionItem() does CHECK(action_id.has_value()) and
#     would crash on a no-action id. The dig:// pages provide their own header,
#     and the toolbar button toggles the panel closed, so no Chromium header /
#     pin-action is needed. (We deliberately do NOT mint a new ActionId: that
#     would require new IDC command ids + grit string resources for no UX gain.)
#   * Registered from SidePanelHelper::PopulateGlobalEntries() -- the one hook
#     where Chromium registers its own global entries (reading list, bookmarks).
#
# Left/right docking is the Side Panel's OWN native pref,
# prefs::kSidePanelHorizontalAlignment ("side_panel.is_right_aligned"; true =
# right [default], false = left). The toolbar buttons flip that pref on
# Alt+click, so the whole side panel follows the chosen edge and it persists per
# profile -- no DIG-specific docking pref is needed.
#
# NOTE: SIDE_PANEL_ENTRY_IDS carries a LINT.IfChange to actions.xml /
# histograms.xml for upstream metrics. This fork does not upload those metrics,
# and the new ids use unique histogram names ("DigWallet"/"DigShields"), so the
# build is unaffected; the xml is intentionally not touched.
#
# BUILD + MANUAL VERIFY (no Chromium build runs in this repo -- follow-up):
#   1. Build the browser (the normal tag/dispatch build workflow).
#   2. Click the DIG Wallet (left-most) toolbar button: dig://wallet must open
#      DOCKED in the Side Panel on the RIGHT, reserving layout space (the page
#      content reflows; the panel is NOT a separate draggable window). Click the
#      button again: the panel closes (Toggle).
#   3. Click the DIG Shields button: dig://shields docks the same way.
#   4. Alt+click either button: the panel re-docks on the LEFT edge (and the
#      choice sticks for Chromium's own side-panel entries too).
#   5. Shift+click either button: the surface opens as a free-floating popup
#      window (the old behavior, now opt-in).
--- a/chrome/browser/ui/side_panel/side_panel_entry_id.h
